---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

// About Stacey — the longer page. Grampy story, philosophy, who
// this is for. Wider measure for narrative breathing.
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Stacey"
  description="About Stacey — the financial coach behind Yellow Legal Pad. Her grandfather, her path, and how she works."
>
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="story-heading">
    <div class="column-wide">
      <h1 id="story-heading">A yellow legal pad and a kitchen table</h1>

      <p>
        Stacey's grandfather &mdash; Grampy &mdash; was the family's financial
        compass for decades. He didn't have credentials or a brokerage. He had
        a yellow legal pad, a felt-tip pen, and an unshakable belief that
        money was something you sat down with people and worked through
        together.
      </p>

      <p>
        Anyone could ask. Cousins, neighbors, the woman who cut his hair, the
        guy who fixed his car. Grampy would pull out the pad, write down what
        was actually happening in plain English, and stay at the kitchen
        table until the numbers stopped feeling like an emergency.
      </p>

      <p>
        He wasn't optimizing returns. He wasn't selling products. He was
        sitting with people. He believed nobody was bad at money &mdash; they
        were just not yet allowed to look at it without flinching.
      </p>

      <p>
        Stacey grew up watching that. The practice she runs today is
        carrying it forward.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* "How she got here" section is held until Stacey provides the
      copy. Restore when the text arrives:

      <section class="section" aria-labelledby="path-heading">
        <div class="column-wide">
          <h2 id="path-heading">How she got here</h2>
          <p>[Stacey's path — career, what led her to coaching.]</p>
          <p>[What she does NOT do — flat fee, not a registered advisor.]</p>
        </div>
      </section>
  */}

  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="philosophy-heading">
    <div class="column">
      <h2 id="philosophy-heading">What she believes</h2>

      <p>
        Most people aren't financially unintelligent. They're
        financially underserved.
      </p>

      <p>
        The financial industry has spent decades making money sound
        complicated, partly because complication justifies fees. Most
        household money decisions are simpler than they look once
        someone calmly explains them.
      </p>

      <p>
        You don't have to wait until you've "fixed everything" to ask
        for help. Wherever you're starting is where we start.
      </p>

      <p>
        Permission matters. Permission to spend on what you love.
        Permission to wash a ziplock bag if it lets you fly first class
        once a year. Permission to want what you want, and to plan for
        it in plain English.
      </p>

      <p>
        Calmness is the most underrated financial skill there is. You
        can do this. You don't need to panic.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="audience-heading">
    <div class="column">
      <h2 id="audience-heading">Who Stacey works with</h2>

      <p>
        Individuals, couples, and families. People in their twenties who
        feel like they should already know this. People in their forties
        who quietly worry it's too late. People taking care of aging
        parents while raising kids. People recently divorced, recently
        widowed, recently inheriting something they didn't expect.
      </p>

      <p>
        Mostly: people who have been smart and capable in every other
        part of their lives, but have never had someone sit down with
        them about money without an agenda.
      </p>

      <p>
        You don't need to have it figured out before you arrive. You
        don't need a spreadsheet. You don't need to bring documents the
        first time.
      </p>

      <p style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">
        <a href="/services">See how Stacey works</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
